    "ADU2": {
      "text": "A principal assumption of this paper is that the notion of a nonmotivating reason is not fundamental, but supervenes on other notions without necessarily being analysable in terms of them.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU3": {
      "text": "It will accordingly have criteria, by which I mean conceptually sufficient conditions, given in terms of these other notions.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU4": {
      "text": "It is also sharp rather than vague - either a reason motivates or it does not.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU5": {
      "text": "Accordingly, it must have sharp criteria.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU6": {
      "text": "So if there are no such criteria there can be no nonmotivating reasons.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU7": {
      "text": "My strategy is to consider a number of seemingly plausible criteria of nonmotivating reasons and to argue that none would be ultimately acceptable to those who believe in such reasons.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU8": {
      "text": "I am thus drawn to the view that there are no nonmotivating reasons.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU9": {
      "text": "And from this I conclude that all rationalising reasons are reasons for which the agent acts, reasons that are causally relevant to, motivate, and explain the agent's action.",
